POPs can travel for incredibly long distances
in the air and water away from their original
sources. Soil is a major repository for POPs,
with inputs including pesticides used in
plants or waste dumps. Despite having been
banned by many countries, POPs, are hard
to break down and continue to persist in the
environment long after their use has ended.
PERSISTENT ORGANIC POLLUTANTS (POPs) ARE TOXIC CHEMICALS THAT CAN BE TRANSPORTED
THROUGH THE AIR AND WATER. THEY ARE USED IN AGRICULTURE, INDUSTRY, AND SOME
HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AS PESTICIDES, SOLVENTS, AND EVEN PHARMACEUTICALS.
POPS CAN TRAVEL THROUGH AIR OR WATER CURRENTS FOR THOUSANDS OF KILOMETERS.
ON WARM DAYS, THEY CAN EVAPORATE IN THE AIR. THEY CAN ALSO TRAVEL LONG DISTANCES
THROUGH A ‘GRASSHOPPER EFFECT’ UNTIL THEY REACH COLD ARCTIC REGIONS.
POPs can be deposited in plants, exposing
wildlife and people to contamination. POPs
accumulate in animal tissues and are not
excreted in body fluids, allowing them to
increase in concentration (a process known as
bioaccumulation.) The higher up on the food

The Stockhold Convention is an international treaty
to protect human health and the environment from
these toxic chemicals. Regulation of POPs can
occur within or outside of the framework of the
chemical groups known as the 'Dirty Dozen' , the
Convention has expanded to target 25 groups.
